# deploy/.env.prod.custom — operator-supplied CUSTOM environment variables.
#
# Copy this file to deploy/.env.prod.custom (gitignored) and add KEY=value
# lines. They are injected DIRECTLY into the container environment of the two
# services that resolve secret references — the `router` and the `mcp_bridge` —
# WITHOUT editing docker-compose.prod.yml.
#
# This exists for secret references you point at from configuration:
#   * An LLM preset's `api_key_ref` = env://MY_PROVIDER_KEY  (router resolves it
#     via bp_router.security.secrets.resolve_secret_ref at call time).
#   * The OIDC client secret as `env://OIDC_CLIENT_SECRET` (router).
#   * An MCP server's `auth_value_ref` = env://SOME_SERVER_TOKEN  (mcp_bridge).
#
# SCOPING — why only router + mcp_bridge, not every container:
#   The suite agents (chatbot, webapp, workers) call the router for LLM work and
#   never resolve secret refs; the sandbox runs UNTRUSTED code. Handing those
#   containers operator secrets would violate least-privilege, so this file is
#   wired only into the two services that actually consume refs. If some other
#   service genuinely needs a custom var, add an `env_file:` to it in the
#   compose file (rare).
#
# PRECEDENCE — vars already listed under a service's `environment:` in the
# compose file WIN over this file. So use this file for NEW names; configure the
# existing slots (GEMINI_API_KEY, ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, OPENAI_API_KEY,
# CUSTOM_LLM_API_KEY_1..3, the ROUTER_OIDC_* block, …) via deploy/.env.prod.
#
# Format: one KEY=value per line (no `export`, no surrounding quotes needed).
# This is a Docker `env_file`, NOT shell — values are taken literally and there
# is no ${VAR} interpolation. KEEP THIS FILE SECRET (chmod 600); never commit
# the filled-in copy.
#
# --- examples (delete or replace) ------------------------------------------
# MY_PROVIDER_KEY=sk-...your-provider-key...
# OIDC_CLIENT_SECRET=...confidential-client-secret...
# SOME_MCP_SERVER_TOKEN=...token-the-stdio-server-needs...
